things is your voice.

00:20:15.470 --> 00:20:16.770
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: Yes.

00:20:16.770 --> 00:20:19.390
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
So when did you realize

00:20:19.390 --> 00:20:23.310
that your voice wasn't working as
well as you had wanted it to work?

00:20:23.310 --> 00:20:25.630
How many years ago was that?

00:20:25.630 --> 00:20:31.950
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: It was 1992
when the problem began.

00:20:31.950 --> 00:20:38.180
And it began because --
and I can verify this

00:20:38.180 --> 00:20:41.870
through Senator Barbara Mikulski --

00:20:41.870 --> 00:20:48.970
I started coughing
[coughs] tiny little coughs.

00:20:48.970 --> 00:20:54.830
And the cough became more
frequent and it reached a point

00:20:54.830 --> 00:20:59.420
where Barbara Mikulski was
coming on to the program

00:20:59.420 --> 00:21:03.510
and she was standing there and
I said, "Senator, forgive me."

00:21:03.510 --> 00:21:05.060
I was in tears.

00:21:05.060 --> 00:21:09.130
I said, "I can't do the interview.

00:21:09.130 --> 00:21:11.240
I can't talk."

00:21:11.240 --> 00:21:20.590
And she said, "If you need me,
I can help get you into NIH."

00:21:20.590 --> 00:21:23.670
She said, "What do you
think the problem is?"

00:21:23.670 --> 00:21:30.280
And I said, "Well, I've
been taking a lot of Advil."

00:21:30.280 --> 00:21:36.890
And she said to me, and you can
check on this, she said to me,

00:21:36.890 --> 00:21:39.560
"You know, that is one

00:21:39.560 --> 00:21:45.710
of the reasons we almost
did not approve Advil

00:21:45.710 --> 00:21:49.150
for over the counter sales.

00:21:49.150 --> 00:21:52.900
But we decided to go
forward with it."

00:21:52.900 --> 00:22:00.520
In any case, in order to get a
diagnosis they kept putting tube

00:22:00.520 --> 00:22:04.790
after tube after tube
down my throat.

00:22:04.790 --> 00:22:10.350
They kept saying to me,
"It's all in your head.

00:22:10.350 --> 00:22:16.830
There's nothing wrong with your
throat or your vocal cords."

00:22:16.830 --> 00:22:27.310
Finally, and I'm going to tell you
how I sounded the day I got off the

00:22:27.310 --> 00:22:28.920
air, [inaudible].

00:22:28.920 --> 00:22:32.350
That's how I sounded.

00:22:32.350 --> 00:22:34.020
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
So you went off the air

00:22:34.020 --> 00:22:36.370
and then you began
a search for doctors

00:22:36.370 --> 00:22:37.670
who could actually diagnose it?

00:22:37.670 --> 00:22:38.970
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: Nope.

00:22:38.970 --> 00:22:44.980
I had already had that
search from 1992 to 1998

00:22:44.980 --> 00:22:49.990
when I finally went off
the air for four months.

00:22:49.990 --> 00:22:54.370
And my doctor finally
called and said,

00:22:54.370 --> 00:22:58.010 position:56%
"We're sending her to Johns Hopkins.

00:22:58.010 --> 00:23:02.010
We've got to find out if
there's cancer somewhere

00:23:02.010 --> 00:23:06.260
