00:33:41.400 --> 00:33:42.700
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: Right.

00:33:42.700 --> 00:33:44.000
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
But what are your views?

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:46.070
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: My views are,

00:33:46.070 --> 00:33:52.560
my views are that I
should have the right

00:33:52.560 --> 00:34:00.510
to choose what I want
for my own death.

00:34:00.510 --> 00:34:06.790
[ Applause ]

00:34:06.790 --> 00:34:08.090
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: Thank you.

00:34:08.090 --> 00:34:11.260 position:56%
And I want to say this very plainly.

00:34:11.260 --> 00:34:18.990
If you believe strongly that
God should be the only decider,

00:34:18.990 --> 00:34:23.530
I support you a thousand percent.

00:34:23.530 --> 00:34:30.540
If you believe that you
want every opportunity

00:34:30.540 --> 00:34:37.180
that medical science
wants, if you want that,

00:34:37.180 --> 00:34:41.000
I support you a thousand percent.

00:34:41.000 --> 00:34:54.270 position:56%
And if you want the right to die
when you believe your time has come,

00:34:54.270 --> 00:34:58.170
I support you a thousand percent.

00:34:58.170 --> 00:35:06.570
So after I step away from
the microphone in January,

00:35:06.570 --> 00:35:14.760
not only am I going to be doing
a weekly podcast, but I am going

00:35:14.760 --> 00:35:22.640
to be speaking out around the
country about the right to choose,

00:35:22.640 --> 00:35:31.370
to choose for yourself how
you want your life to end.

00:35:31.370 --> 00:35:32.740
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
Now there are some states

00:35:32.740 --> 00:35:34.110
that allow to do that.

00:35:34.110 --> 00:35:35.750
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: Five.

00:35:35.750 --> 00:35:37.840
Oregon became the first.

00:35:37.840 --> 00:35:41.310
California, the most recent.

00:35:41.310 --> 00:35:50.650
And like the right to marry
the person you choose,

00:35:50.650 --> 00:35:54.780 position:56%
California became the tipping point.

00:35:54.780 --> 00:36:00.930
I believe the same is true
with death with dignity.

00:36:00.930 --> 00:36:06.270 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So you'll be
doing that after you end your show.

00:36:06.270 --> 00:36:09.370
Now, in your book you
talk about what it's

00:36:09.370 --> 00:36:12.950
like after your husband did
die and you had to adjust

00:36:12.950 --> 00:36:16.450
to not only living alone, but
having no partner any longer.

00:36:16.450 --> 00:36:19.500
And can you describe what
that feeling was like

00:36:19.500 --> 00:36:24.450
and how you have tried to adjust
in dealing with your friends

00:36:24.450 --> 00:36:27.100
and reacquainting yourself
with other people

00:36:27.100 --> 00:36:28.450
because you now have more time.

00:36:28.450 --> 00:36:34.160
But how do you describe
what the phenomenon it is?

00:36:34.160 --> 00:36:41.950
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: I think the
grief, the feeling of loss,

00:36:41.950 --> 00:36:48.960
the yearning for that person
there at breakfast, or at dinner,

00:36:48.960 --> 00:36:53.700
or talking about what's
in the newspaper,

00:36:53.700 --> 00:36:57.350
I don't think that ever goes away.

00:36:57.350 --> 00:37:06.390 position:56%
I think the idea of closure at least
in my own mind has never existed.

00:37:06.390 --> 00:37:12.860
I think the loved ones we
lose are always with us.

00:37:12.860 --> 00:37:20.150
And every time I stand at my window
on the fourteenth floor of my condo

00:37:20.150 --> 00:37:26.120
and it's windows all
along facing west

00:37:26.120 --> 00:37:31.800
and watching the sunset
I think of John.

00:37:31.800 --> 00:37:37.770
I believe that I have
expanded my friendships.

00:37:37.770 --> 00:37:47.000
I've intensified my relationships
with people and I am realizing

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:55.510
that 54 years that we
had were extraordinary

00:37:55.510 --> 00:38:00.830
and precious but life goes on.

00:38:00.830 --> 00:38:07.870
And my life does go
on and we shall see.

00:38:07.870 --> 00:38:10.360
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
So your children live

00:38:10.360 --> 00:38:13.470
in different cities now so
they're not living here.

00:38:13.470 --> 00:38:14.770
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: Right.

00:38:14.770 --> 00:38:16.070
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:

00:38:16.070 --> 00:38:17.500
And so therefore you're
grandchildren are not living

00:38:17.500 --> 00:38:18.800
here either?

00:38:18.800 --> 00:38:20.100
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: No.

00:38:20.100 --> 00:38:22.370
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So have you
decided that you'll, post-January,

00:38:22.370 --> 00:38:26.490
you'll put a lot of time
into this advocacy work?

00:38:26.490 --> 00:38:27.790
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: Indeed.

00:38:27.790 --> 00:38:29.090
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein:
And the podcast?

00:38:29.090 --> 00:38:33.450
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: I already have
three speaking appointments lined

00:38:33.450 --> 00:38:38.050
up next year for this kind of work.

00:38:38.050 --> 00:38:43.610
And I will be doing
a weekly podcast.

00:38:43.610 --> 00:38:52.290
I hope you will all send to WAMU
your own email addresses so that

00:38:52.290 --> 00:38:58.510 position:56%
when the podcast comes out we'll be
able to connect with you right away.

00:38:58.510 --> 00:39:01.540
[ Applause ]

00:39:01.540 --> 00:39:04.630 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: So as you
look back on 37 years of doing this,

00:39:04.630 --> 00:39:07.100
what would you say is
the highlight of it?

00:39:07.100 --> 00:39:09.220
Is it that you had 37 years?

00:39:09.220 --> 00:39:10.550
You met so many interesting people?

00:39:10.550 --> 00:39:12.820
You have so many people around
the country listen to you?

00:39:12.820 --> 00:39:16.160
What has been the greatest pleasure
out of doing this for 37 years?

00:39:16.160 --> 00:39:18.610
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: The
greatest pleasure, David,

00:39:18.610 --> 00:39:26.750
has been the opportunity to
listen, to be in the same room

00:39:26.750 --> 00:39:33.920
with all these wonderful guests,
to learn because I think one

00:39:33.920 --> 00:39:38.540
of the advantages for
me of not going

00:39:38.540 --> 00:39:44.290 position:56%
to college is that I yearn to learn.

00:39:44.290 --> 00:39:51.690
And I have learned every
single day of these 37 years.

00:39:51.690 --> 00:39:57.200
What perhaps I would never
have had the opportunity

00:39:57.200 --> 00:40:02.170 position:56%
to do had I simply been lectured to.

00:40:02.170 --> 00:40:07.050
I'm not a good person to
sit and be lectured to.

00:40:07.050 --> 00:40:09.780
I need to push back a little bit.

00:40:09.780 --> 00:40:11.080
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Right.

00:40:11.080 --> 00:40:12.380
And do your children
give you any advice

00:40:12.380 --> 00:40:15.120 position:56%
about what they thing you should do?

00:40:15.120 --> 00:40:16.420
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: Ah.

00:40:16.420 --> 00:40:21.250
No. They keep saying, "Mom,
you're doing too much."

00:40:21.250 --> 00:40:24.000
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: Well, I
want to thank you on behalf of all

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:26.510
of the listeners who listen
to you for so many years.

00:40:26.510 --> 00:40:29.900
I have been one of them and I
was a guest not too long ago.

00:40:29.900 --> 00:40:31.200
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: Indeed.

00:40:31.200 --> 00:40:32.500
&gt;&gt; David M. Rubenstein: And on
behalf of everybody here I want

00:40:32.500 --> 00:40:34.570
to thank you but I also
want to give you a gift.

00:40:34.570 --> 00:40:37.310
And can the person who
has the gift bring it?

00:40:37.310 --> 00:40:38.780
Here it is.

00:40:38.780 --> 00:40:40.930
This is your, you just
celebrated your eightieth birthday.

00:40:40.930 --> 00:40:42.230
&gt;&gt; Diane Rehm: I did.

